Students in Harvard on a course for enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year causes all students to sleep more in an effort to tackle the growing culture of learning “all night” with the help of caffeine.
A teacher found that students at the number one university in the world often do not even think when it comes to the very basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Caissler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Hospital and Women’s Hospital, prepared the course he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“Another girl came to me and said, ‘Why are they telling me this right now, in my last year?’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is held for the first time this year, explains to students what is most essential about how good sleep habits help academic and sports achievements, as well as to improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university has decided to introduce the course after it was found that students suffer from a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one part there is an image of a room in a dormitory where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, marathons and books to explain to them the effects of caffeine and light, how sports achievements are affected by lack of sleep, as well as the importance of sleep routine.
In another part of the participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Then a map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not immediately change the behavior of the students.
But we believe they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke,” added Prof. Caissler.
The culture of pride from “learning all night” still exists, he said, adding that modern technologies and ever-increasing pressure on students mean that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Providing adequate and high-quality sleep should be the students’ “secret weapon” in the fight against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he says – even in order to avoid overcrowding, as sleep deprivation brings the brain into a mode of hunger, which makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond Soe, a 19-year-old student from California who studied chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Caissler prepare the course by taking one of his first-year classes at Harvard.
He says his course “opened his eyes” and inspired him to spread it throughout the campus.
It is hoped that the next step is for all graduate students to be asked to complete a similar curriculum before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Caissler advises students to think about setting up a sleep and wake-up alarm and to know the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can upset the circadian rhythm and cause the problem to occur.
