How the U.S.-China trade war could serve Beijing
The first shots in the U.S.-China trade war were deafening and, while the battle is still speeding up, a split between the two countries will benefit Beijing in the long run, experts say.
Donald Trump, the president of the United States, fired the first warning wave this year by taxing key elements of China’s exports, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The biggest escalation of tensions has emerged this week with new tariffs affecting $200 billion in production (<0xC2><0xA3>150 billion) with an effective tax on half of all goods imported into the United States from China.
Each time, Beijing returned new tariffs with five to ten percent of U.S. goods for $60 billion.
China has vowed to retaliate to any U.S. blow, and soon the world’s second-largest economy is not expected to ignore it.
To make Washington give up means to submit to demands, but to bring down a head publicly in front of Washington would be too shameful for Xi Jinping, the president of China.
And yet, according to experts, if Beijing plays its cards correctly, the pressure from the U.S. trade war could help China in the long run by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that an accelerated political decision in both Washington and Beijing could create conditions for an economic crisis in one of the two countries is actually more dangerous than the observers have previously acknowledged,” Abigail Grace, an expert on the issue, told the Associated Press.
Syria is “ready” for the return of refugees, the foreign minister said.
Syria said it was ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asked for assistance in restoring the country devastated by the war, which lasted more than seven years.
In a speech to the UN General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Mualem said the conditions in the country were improving.
“Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and safe, thanks to the progress we have made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to restore the areas devastated by the terrorists to bring them back to their normal state.
There are now all conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to the country that they were forced to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures that have affected their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the start of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living there are in need of humanitarian assistance.
Al-Mualem said the Syrian regime would welcome any assistance in restoring the devastated state.
But he stressed that conditional aid or assistance will not be accepted from countries that have financed the rebels.
